task.summary: Default task
PR fixes

Add 'keyDown' and 'keyUp' implementation (17.4.2)
* Added ReentrantLock to prevent uiadapter from being concurrently operated on by different threads

Implement 'perform a pointer move' algorithm
* Add adapter methods * Update dummy adapter to simply track pointer move events * Added 'pointerDispatch' class that does perform move algorithm

Make 'perform a pointer move' iterative instead of recursive
* Doing it recursively opens a new thread every call * This way makes it run on just the one thread
Implement 'dispatch pointer move' algorithm
Return callables instead of futures
Implement dispatch pointer down and dispatch pointer up algorithms
Add docs
Can dispatch a single Tick
Implement action sequence processing algorithm in 17.4
Fix key actions and pause issues
PR fixes

Move W3C process events to separate package and classes
* Instead of having all the processor methods in the W3CActions class create a new package called 'Processor' and have a separate class for actions, key, pause, pointer processors and have a helper class

Move W3C process events to separate package and classes
* Add 'cancel list' to InputStateTable * Add a KeyUp action object to cancel list when KeyDown is called * Created a copy constructor to create ActionObject * Other * Moved 'active input sources' to 'state' package
Make 'pointerDown' cancellable
Implement 'perform actions' algorith (17.5)

Move 'dispatch' into an ActionObject member method
* Refactored Tick.java to use this method * Did it so that we could run dispatches in multiple places without re-writing the logic
Moved the logic for getting or creating input state into InputStateTable
Move 'KeyEvent' into it's own class
Can undo keydown events
Add release algorithm (17.6)
Made origin type that can parse element types too
Refactored everything to use origin

Make logger an Android logger that implements a logger interface
...so that in /actions we can use a logger that doesn't have any Android dependencies and can be run in a unit test
Add logging to the actions

Make pointerMove events run in the main thread
* Can't run Espresso pointer movement events in a separate thread * The fix is to have the performPointerMove return an object in the callable that has a 'perform' method that executes the callable, as well as a reference to the _next_ callable that is run * Now, the main thread calls 'perform' and then async calls whatever is "next"
Add pointer cancel event
Calculate metaState for pointer events
Add 'view-tag' as an element attribute
Add '-android viewtag' selector strategy
Map unicode key values to Android KeyEvents

Allow Int or String for key action values
* Not all of the keys in Android Key Events can be represented by a single unicode character, some have no obvious mapping (like https://developer.android.com/reference/android/view/KeyEvent.html#KEYCODE_TV_ANTENNA_CABLE for example) * To work around this, we'll tweak it so that we accept numbers as well as single unicode text strings so that we can input the Android Key Event numbers
Add meta state and test that uses the 'SHIFT' key to confirm
PR fixes
PR fixes

Fix problems with getElementCenterPoint in /actions api
* Use `view.isShown` to check if an element is stale instead of the view-interaction method * Change element key to `element-6066-11e4-a52e-4f735466cecf` * Make `getElementCenterPoint`return Point instead of long[] * Added test for `/actions` on an element

Add /keys endpoint
* Took the approach of simply creating the equivalent /actions events that /keys endpoint would translate to
Add /actions release endpoint
Add builder pattern

Make Keys handler release key actions when done
* The global meta state should be released after 'keys' is called * Also fixed the undoAll... don't call 'keyUp' if key is already released

Make Keys handler release key actions when done
* The global meta state should be released after 'keys' is called * Also fixed the undoAll... don't call 'keyUp' if key is already released

Add single touch actions
* Changed sleep method to use `uiController.loopMainThreadForAtLeast` instead of `SystemClock.sleep`. `SystemClock.sleep` was delaying UI changes * Rename performActions and releaseActions to 'perform' and 'release' * Add more logging
Callable should be using Thread.sleep and not SystemClock or the UiController sleep methods

Fix finger identifier
* Don't check that x,y is positive.... we can have negative x,y relative to element/pointer * Add tests for multi touch (they work!)

Fix: Call 'synchronousTickActionsComplete' after undoAll is called
* Calling 'undoAll' dispatches all of the release events but doesn't call them * Dispatching queues up TOUCH events but doesn't invoke them until 'synchronousTickActionsComplete' is called * This is because TOUCH events need to be grouped together so that they can comply with Android's "consistency guarantee" (`For touch events, consistency implies that pointers go down one at a time, move around as a group and then go up one at a time or are canceled`)

Convert mouse to touch events if touchscreen device
* Checks if the device has a touch screen, and if it does assume mouse events are to be converted to touch * This is because some clients only do mouse and we want those clients to still be usable on touchscreen * Also * Check downEvent is null before setting 'source' on pointer event. Pointer events don't always have * Improved logging for 'inject' event exception. Inject event always means it was outside the viewport

* Don't check that x,y is positive.... we can have negative x,y relative to element/pointer * Add tests for multi touch (they work!)

Fix: Call 'synchronousTickActionsComplete' after undoAll is called
* Calling 'undoAll' dispatches all of the release events but doesn't call them * Dispatching queues up TOUCH events but doesn't invoke them until 'synchronousTickActionsComplete' is called * This is because TOUCH events need to be grouped together so that they can comply with Android's "consistency guarantee" (`For touch events, consistency implies that pointers go down one at a time, move around as a group and then go up one at a time or are canceled`)

* Checks if the device has a touch screen, and if it does assume mouse events are to be converted to touch * This is because some clients only do mouse and we want those clients to still be usable on touchscreen * Also * Check downEvent is null before setting 'source' on pointer event.
